Rust equivalents found:
  emThread class:
    - Not ported as a type. Rust uses std::thread::scope() and std::thread::spawn() directly.
    - emRenderThreadPool.rs:77 uses std::thread::scope (replaces C++ emThread + emThreadEvent
      activate/done pattern)
    - emProcess.rs:6 uses std::thread (for process I/O pump)
  emThread::GetHardwareThreadCount():
    - emRenderThreadPool.rs:35 uses std::thread::available_parallelism()
  emThreadMiniMutex:
    - Not ported. Rust code uses std::sync::Mutex instead.
    - emStd1.rs:8 uses std::sync::Mutex
    - emStd1.rs:10 uses std::sync::atomic::AtomicBool
    - emPainter.rs:6429, emViewRenderer.rs:60, emWindow.rs:425 use std::sync::Mutex
  emThreadMutex (readers/writers):
    - Not ported. No RwLock usage found in Rust emCore.
    - C++ emFontCache uses emThreadMutex; OPEN QUESTION: how Rust emFontCache handles concurrency.
  emThreadEvent (semaphore):
    - Not ported. Rust replaces the activate/done event pattern with
      std::thread::scope (scoped thread join replaces explicit event signaling).
  emThreadRecursiveMutex:
    - Not ported. No usage found in Rust emCore.
  emThreadMutexLocker:
    - Not needed. Rust's MutexGuard provides RAII locking.
  emThreadId:
    - Not ported. std::thread::ThreadId used implicitly by std::thread API.

Coverage gaps:
  - emThread::StartUnmanaged (detached thread spawning) - no Rust equivalent found
  - emThread::ExitCurrentThread - no Rust equivalent found (not typically needed in Rust)
  - emThread::WaitForTermination with timeout - no Rust equivalent found
    (std::thread::JoinHandle::join has no timeout)
  - emThread::GetExitStatus - no Rust equivalent found (thread closures return values via JoinHandle)
  - emThreadEvent (full semaphore API) - no Rust equivalent found; functionality replaced
    by scoped threads in the one known usage site (emRenderThreadPool)
  - emThreadMutex with readers/writers and timeout - no Rust equivalent found
  - emThreadRecursiveMutex - no Rust equivalent found

OPEN QUESTIONS:
  - How does Rust emFontCache handle concurrent access? C++ uses emThreadMutex.
  - C++ emPainter accepts a userSpaceMutex (emThreadMiniMutex*) parameter for thread safety
    during painting. How is this handled in the Rust port? Rust emPainter.rs uses
    std::sync::Mutex for tile results, but the userSpaceMutex parameter pattern is unclear.
  - Are any of the "coverage gap" methods actually needed by the Rust port, or are they
    all dead code paths in the emCore-only scope?

