================================================================================
REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

C++ emThread.h: portable threading primitives wrapping pthreads/Win32.

19 files outside emCore use this type.

C++ defines these types:
  emThread                  — managed thread with start/join/exit status
  emThreadMiniMutex         — lightweight non-recursive mutex
  emThreadMutex             — reader/writer mutex with timeout
  emThreadRecursiveMutex    — recursive mutex
  emThreadEvent             — counting semaphore
  emThreadMutexLocker<T>    — RAII lock guard
  emThreadId                — thread identifier typedef

Rust equivalents used in the codebase (verified by grep):
  emThread             -> std::thread::scope() in emRenderThreadPool.rs
  emThreadMiniMutex    -> std::sync::Mutex in emViewRenderer.rs, emPainter.rs, emWindow.rs
                          AtomicUsize in emRenderThreadPool.rs
  emThreadEvent        -> std::thread::scope auto-join (no explicit signaling)
  GetHardwareThreadCount -> std::thread::available_parallelism()

No Rust equivalent exists for:
  emThread::StartUnmanaged     — detached thread spawning
  emThread::ExitCurrentThread  — terminate current thread
  emThread::WaitForTermination with timeout
  emThread::GetExitStatus      — integer exit code from thread
  emThreadMutex                — reader/writer lock with timeout
  emThreadRecursiveMutex       — recursive mutex
  emThreadEvent full API       — counting semaphore send/receive with timeout
  emPainter userSpaceMutex parameter — mutex passed into painter for
    thread-safe paint callbacks

Architectural difference in the rendering pipeline:
  C++ emViewRenderer runs user paint code on worker threads. Each thread
  holds a userSpaceMutex (emThreadMiniMutex) that user code can
  unlock/relock during painting. This requires emThread primitives.

  Rust emViewRenderer records paint ops single-threaded (emPainterDrawList),
  then replays them in parallel. User paint code never runs on worker
  threads. The userSpaceMutex pattern does not exist in Rust.
  This change was made because Rc (used for panel state) is not Send.

NOT VERIFIED: whether any of the 19 outside-emCore files use emThread
  primitives in ways that are not covered by std::thread / std::sync.
